post_text: Misty Wolfe, Career and Technical Education Coordinator for the Randolph County School System, is the 2020-2021 Curriculum and Instructional Management Coordinator (CIMC) of the Year for the State of North Carolina! Ms. Wolfe was selected as the Piedmont-Triad Regional CIMC of the Year by her peers in our region on May 22, and today, at the NC CTE Virtual Summer Conference, she was announced as the state CIMC of the Year and will represent NC at the Region II ACTE Conference this fall. This is certainly a well-deserved honor for the outstanding work Ms. Wolfe does to support our students, teachers, parents, and administrators and CTE efforts at the state, regional, and national level!
text: Misty Wolfe, Career and Technical Education Coordinator for the Randolph County School System, is the 2020-2021 Curriculum and Instructional Management Coordinator (CIMC) of the Year for the State of North Carolina! Ms. Wolfe was selected as the Piedmont-Triad Regional CIMC of the Year by her peers in our region on May 22, and today, at the NC CTE Virtual Summer Conference, she was announced as the state CIMC of the Year and will represent NC at the Region II ACTE Conference this fall. This is certainly a well-deserved honor for the outstanding work Ms. Wolfe does to support our students, teachers, parents, and administrators and CTE efforts at the state, regional, and national level!

post_text: Nancy Cross, Director of Career-Technical Education, Innovative School Design, and 6-8 Instruction for the Randolph County School System, has received the "Carl Perkins Community Service Award" from the NC Association for Career and Technical Education! The award honors the significant impact Ms. Cross has made on our community and her demonstrated leadership in programs and activities that promote student involvement in community service. Ms. Cross will represent North Carolina as a regional and national competitor in the 2022 ACTE Excellence Awards program.
text: Nancy Cross, Director of Career-Technical Education, Innovative School Design, and 6-8 Instruction for the Randolph County School System, has received the "Carl Perkins Community Service Award" from the NC Association for Career and Technical Education! We need your feedback!

RCSS is required to develop and implement a Remote Instruction Plan for the 2020-2021 school year based on legislation passed on May 21, 2020, in response to the COVID-19 crisis.

The Plan will provide a framework for delivering quality remote instruction to all students within RCSS during the 2020-2021 school year.

Here is the Plan: https://content.schoolinsites.com/api/documents/015e5c68f35a4073aac24317274c45a3.pdf

Thank you!

Each school year, RCSS presents an Outstanding Employee Award at each of our 31 schools.

The Outstanding Employee Award honors the classified employee from each school who has made a significant impact on the quality of education at his/her school. All school-based classified employees are eligible for this award. Employees are nominated and selected by peers at their school.

Here are our Outstanding Employees the 2019-2020 school year!

post_text: This song was written by Ethan Cahoon, a senior at South Lenoir High School of Lenoir County Public Schools in Deep Run, NC. Ethan was moved by the enormity of change in our world and in the progression of his senior year. He said he wanted to share something positive with his fellow seniors and with others. Ethan shared his lyrics with classmate and fellow senior, Avery Harper, who took a couple of days to write music to accompany the lyrics from Ethan. Ethan and Avery worked out their song as Avery sang. They brought in another senior, Arielle Winn, to harmonize with Avery. These students are not professional musicians. They are just kids who wanted to help others. Together, they created a very moving song dedicated to the Class of 2020. Just wanted to share.
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
It's Gonna Be Okay (Senior Tribute Song)
text:
This song was written by Ethan Cahoon, a senior at South Lenoir High School of Lenoir County Public Schools in Deep Run, NC. Ethan was moved by the enormity of change in our world and in the progression of his senior year. He said he wanted to share something positive with his fellow seniors and with others. Ethan shared his lyrics with classmate and fellow senior, Avery Harper, who took a couple of days to write music to accompany the lyrics from Ethan. Ethan and Avery worked out their song as Avery sang. They brought in another senior, Arielle Winn, to harmonize with Avery. These students are not professional musicians. They are just kids who wanted to help others. Together, they created a very moving song dedicated to the Class of 2020. Just wanted to share.

post_text: Thank you to Randolph County 4-H for providing at-home ‚ÄúGardening Kits‚Äù for every 5th grader in RCSS! Thank you, also, to Southern States of Asheboro, the NC Farm to School Coalition, and Randolph County Cooperative Extension for sponsoring this initiative. Each kit includes pots, seeds, soil, planting instructions, a Gardening Packet with pages of resources, and more. Principals and other staff members from our elementary schools stopped by our central office today to pick up the kits. The kits will be included in the instructional packets being distributed to students tomorrow.

post_text:
UPDATE ON OUR EMERGENCY FEEDING PROGRAM

During school closures, we will continue to provide one breakfast and one lunch meal per day for children 18 years of age and younger.

Breakfast and lunch meals are available for pick-up at Archdale Elementary, Franklinville Elementary, Liberty Elementary, Ramseur Elementary, Randleman Elementary, Randleman Middle, Seagrove Elementary, Southmont Elementary, Tabernacle Elementary, and Trinity Elementary.

Beginning Monday, April 27, families will be able to pick up breakfast meals and lunch meals at the same time. Hours for pick-up will be 11:00 a.m. to 12:30 p.m., Monday through Friday.

Delivery sites will remain on the same schedule as before, but will now provide both a breakfast meal and lunch meal for each child. All delivery sites and times are posted here: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1Lks6Uw0yTmMI8ZJqVDjwKijEe2_mXVcr

If you have any questions, please call RCSS School Nutrition Services at (336) 633-5161.

post_text: School Nutrition staff members at Ramseur Elementary, bus drivers, and bus monitors work together to deliver lunches to children up to age 18 in Randolph County. Over the past three days, nearly 4,000 free meals have been provided by RCSS. We currently have 4 "feeding sites," but that number will soon increase to 9 sites. Also, we currently have 15 "delivery sites," but that number will be increasing, as well. Children do not need to be a part of our school system to receive a free meal. For a complete list of our current feeding sites and delivery sites, please go to the RCSS website and click the appropriate links near the top of the home page: https://www.randolph.k12.nc.us/

post_text: At 4:30 p.m. today, Governor Roy Cooper ordered the closure of all public schools in North Carolina for students for at least two weeks starting on 3/16/20. With this decision, Monday (3/16/20) is now an optional teacher workday for staff members. The plan for staff members for the other days affected by this school closure will be shared on Monday (3/16/20) upon our receipt of guidance from the state. Thank you for your patience as we move through this difficult time.
text: At 4:30 p.m. today, Governor Roy Cooper ordered the closure of all public schools in North Carolina for students for at least two weeks starting on 3/16/20. With this decision, Monday (3/16/20) is now an optional teacher workday for staff members. The plan for staff members for the other days affected by this school closure will be shared on Monday (3/16/20) upon our receipt of guidance from the state. Thank you for your patience as we move through this difficult time.
